        <name>14.4.1.1 Exercise 1</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Find the length of the line \(y = {@y@}\) between \(x = {@a@}\) and \(x = {@b@}\) using the technique of this Section. Verify your result from your knowledge of the straight line. Give your answer in &lt;b&gt;exact&lt;/b&gt; form.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The length is [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;The distance is from \(({@a@},{@y_a@})\) to \(({@b@},{@y_b@})\) along the line. This is given using Pythagoras' theorem as \(\sqrt{({@b@}-{@a@})^2+({@y_b@}-{@y_a@})^2}={@ta1@} \)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Using the formula \[\text{length of curve}=\int_a^b \sqrt{1+\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right)^2}\&amp;nbsp; \mathrm{d}x,\] the length of the line is calculated to be \[\int_{{@a@}}^{{@b@}} \sqrt{1+({@dy@})^2} \ \mathrm{d}x={@ta1@}.\]&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
